/PL755/XX/PR

I look up to the sky and the stars,/PR

And down to the earth and the things that creep there,/PR

And I consider in my heart how their creation/PR

Was planned with wisdom in every detail./PR

See the heavens above like a tent,/PR

Constructed with loops and hooks,/PR

And the moon with its stars, like a shepherdess/PR

Sending her sheep into the reeds;/PR

The moon itself among the clouds,/PR

Like a ship sailing under its banners;/PR

The clouds like a girl in her garden/PR

Moving, and watering the myrtle-trees;/PR

The dew-mist--a woman shaking/PR

Drops from her hair to the ground./PR

The inhabitants turn, like animals, to rest,/PR

(Their palaces are their stables);/PR

And all fleeing from the fear of death,/PR

Like a dove pursued by the falcon./PR

And these are compared at the end to a plate/PR

Which is smashed into innumerable shards./PR

Shmuel Hanagid/XX/PR

/KAWhere We Can Find God/XX/PR

Where will I find God/PR

Whose glory fills the universe?/PR

/PR

I find God/PR

Wherever the farmer ploughs a furrow through the hard soil,/PR

Wherever the quarryman pounds the stone to gravel,/PR

Wherever one earns her bread by the sweat of her brow,/PR

In the company of the friendless, the afflicted, the lowly, the/PR



lost,/PR


There God abides in sun and shower./PI/PR

/PR

/PR

/PR

/PG756/XX/PR

I find God/PR

Wherever the mind is free to follow its own bent,/PR

Wherever words come out from the depth of truth,/PR

Wherever tireless striving stretches its arms toward perfection,/PR

Wherever people struggle for freedom and right,/PR

Wherever the scientist toils to unbare the secrets of nature,/PR

Wherever the poet strings pearls of beauty in lyric lines,/PR


Wherever glorious deeds are done./PR

/PR

I find God/PR

In the merry shouts of children at play,/PR

In the lullaby the mother sings, rocking her baby to sleep,/PR

In the slumber that falls on the infantòs eyelids,/PR


And in the smile that plays on his sleeping lips./PR

/PR

I find God/PR

When the dawn comes with her golden cornucopia,/PR

Or when evening falls, bringing peace and rest from the/PR



Western ocean of rest./PR

God is in the joy that streams from heaven with the morning/PR



light,/PR

In the current of life that courses day and night through my/PR



sinews and through all nature,/PR

In the life that throbs exultant in the dust of the earth and/PR



through the blades of grass innumerable,/PR


And that flows, in a multitude of tempestuous waves, through/PR



the leaves and flowers./PR

/PR

I find God/PR

In the wealth of those passing delights that live but for a/PR



moment,/PR

In the pulsebeat of a life that comes from eternity and dances/PR



in my own blood,/PR

In birth that keeps renewing the generations,/PR


And in death that keeps knocking on the doors of life./PR

Rabindranath Tagore (translated and adapted)/XX/PR

/PR

/PR

/PR

/PL757/XX/PR

/KAGod The Life of Nature/XX/PR

Our ancestors acclaimed the God/PR

Whose handiwork they read/PR

In the mysterious heavens above,/PR

And in the varied scene of earth below,/PR

In the orderly march of days and nights,/PR

Of seasons and years,/PR

And in the checkered fate of humankind./PR

/PR

Night reveals the limitless caverns of space,/PR

Hidden by the light of day,/PR

And unfolds horizonless vistas/PR

Far beyond imaginationòs ken./PR

The mind is staggered,/PR

Yet soon regains its poise,/PR

And peering through the boundless dark,/PR

Orients itself anew/PR

By the light of distant suns/PR

Shrunk to glittering sparks./PR

The soul is faint,/PR

Yet soon revives,/PR

And learns to spell once more the name of God/PR

Across the newly visioned firmament./PR

/PR


Lift your eyes, look up;/PR


Who made these stars?/PR

/PR

God is the oneness/PR

That spans the fathomless deeps of space/PR

And the measureless eons of time,/PR

Binding them together in deed,/PR

As we do in thought./PI/PR

/PR

/PR

/PR

/PG758/XX/PR

God is the sameness/PR

In the elemental substance of stars and planets,/PR

Of this our earthly abode/PR

And of all that it holds./PR

/PR

God is the unity/PR

Of all that is,/PR

The uniformity of all that moves,/PR

The rhythm of all things/PR

And the nature of their interaction./PR

/PR

God is the mystery of life,/PR

Enkindling inert matter/PR

With inner drive and purpose./PR

/PR

God is the creative flame/PR

That transfigures lifeless substance,/PR

Leaping into ever higher realms of being,/PR

Brightening into the radiant glow of feeling,/PR

Till it runs into the white fire of thought./PR

/PR

And though no sign of living things/PR

Breaks the eternal silence of the spheres,/PR

We cannot deem this earth,/PR

This tiny speck in the infinitude,/PR

Alone instinct with God./PR

/PR

By that token/PR

Which unites the worlds in bonds of matter/PR

Are all the worlds bound/PR

In the bond of Life./PR

/PR

God is in the faith/PR

By which we overcome/PR

The fear of loneliness, of helplessness,/PR

Of failure and of death./PI/PR

/PR

/PR

/PR

/PL759/XX/PR

God is in the hope/PR

Which, like a shaft of light,/PR

Cleaves the dark abysms/PR

Of sin, of suffering, and of despair./PR

/PR

God is in the love/PR

Which creates, protects, forgives./PR

/PR

It is Godòs spirit/PR

That broods upon the chaos we have wrought,/PR

Disturbing its static wrongs,/PR

And stirring into life the formless beginnings/PR

Of the new and better world./PR

Mordecai M. Kaplan (adapted)/XX/PR

/KAIn Praise/XX/PR

GENESIS 1, 2/PR

/PR

Hail the hand that scattered space with stars,/PR

Wrapped whirling world in bright blue blanket, air,/PR

Made worlds within worlds, elements in earth,/PR

Souls within skins, every one a teeming universe,/PR

Every tree a system of semantics, and pushed/PR

Beyond probability to place consciousness/PR

On this cooling crust of burning rock./PR

/PR

Oh praise that hand, mind, heart, soul, power or force/PR

That so inclosed, separated, limited planets, trees, humans/PR

Yet breaks all bounds and borders/PR

To lavish on us light, love, life/PR

This trembling glory./PR

Ruth Brin/XX/PR

/PR

/PR

/PR

/PG760/XX/PR

/KATrees/XX/PR

To be a giant and keep quiet about it,/PR

To stay in oneòs own place;/PR

To stand for the constant presence of process/PR

And always to seem the same;/PR

To be steady as a rock and always trembling,/PR

Having the hard appearance of death/PR

With the soft, fluent nature of growth,/PR

Oneòs Being deceptively armored,/PR

Oneòs Becoming deceptively vulnerable;/PR

To be so tough, and take the light so well,/PR

Freely providing forbidden knowledge/PR

Of so many things about heaven and earth/PR

For which we should otherwise have no word--/PR

Poems or people are rarely so lovely,/PR

And even when they have great qualities/PR

They tend to tell you rather than exemplify/PR

What they believe themselves to be about,/PR

While from the moving silence of trees,/PR

Whether in storm or calm, in leaf and naked,/PR

Night or day, we draw conclusions of our own,/PR

Sustaining and unnoticed as our breath,/PR

And perilous also--though there has never been/PR

A critical tree--about the nature of things./PR

Howard Nemerov/XX/PR

/PR

